# Reflective Proposal

Through my Making Journal, I explored different ways of working with data, including data collection, visualisation, and live data interaction. Among these experiments, I particularly enjoyed the process of collecting and visualising my own data, such as tracking phone usage and emotional states. Compared to working with external datasets, I found this approach more engaging and meaningful, as it allowed for creative interpretation and personal reflection. It also gave me more freedom to experiment with visual forms rather than focusing only on technical accuracy.
Based on this, I want to continue exploring the relationship between emotional data and everyday behaviour. My project will focus on how personal data, such as phone usage patterns, could be used to interpret psychological states like loneliness, boredom, or curiosity. I am especially interested in how this kind of data might be used in a future scenario where emotional and behavioural data is continuously collected and analysed by AI systems.
In this imagined future, mobile devices or AI systems could automatically track and interpret patterns of behaviour in order to assess mental health or emotional wellbeing. For example, late-night phone usage, repetitive checking behaviour, or periods of inactivity might be used as indicators of loneliness or stress  (I noticed that I tend to use my phone more at night, especially when I feel bored or restless). While this could potentially support mental health awareness, it also raises questions about surveillance, interpretation, and control over personal data. To explore this idea, I plan to use a combination of self-collected data and simulated data. I will interpret patterns such as time of use, frequency, and emotional categories, and translate them into visual elements. This approach connects to ideas of data humanism, as it focuses on representing data as lived experience rather than abstract numbers. It also relates to data feminism (D’Ignazio & Klein, 2020), particularly the idea that data is not neutral and should be understood in relation to context, power, and interpretation.
The visualisation will be developed using p5.js and will be interactive. Rather than presenting the data as a standard chart, I aim to create a more expressive and atmospheric visual system, where emotional states and behavioural patterns are represented through movement, colour, and spatial relationships. For example, different emotional states might be visualised as shifting forms or patterns that respond to user interaction.
The goal of this project is to encourage viewers to reflect on how their everyday behaviours could be interpreted as data, and how these interpretations might shape their understanding of themselves. I want the audience to question whether data-driven interpretations of mental health are helpful, reductive, or potentially misleading. Ultimately, the project aims to shift the perception of data from something purely objective to something that is constructed, interpretive, and deeply connected to human experience.

